04262nam a22007095i 9780292748798DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927487987 a10.7560/7358352doi  a(DE-B1597)588400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aTJ820 ǂb G35 2013eb 7aBUS0700402bisacsh04a333.92097641 aGalbraith, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great Texas Wind Rush :bHow George Bush, Ann Richards, and a Bunch of Tinkerers Helped the Oil and Gas State Win the Race to Wind Power /cKate Galbraith, Asher Price. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Following a Glider -- t2. The Tinkerers -- t3. The Oil Embargo -- t4. The 1980s -- t5. Ann Richards—and a Big Wind Farm at Last -- t6. Windcatters -- t7. A Wind Requirement -- t8. The Next Decade: Takeoff -- t9. The Future -- t10. The Lessons of Texas Wind -- tPostscript -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late 1990s, West Texas was full of rundown towns and pumpjacks, aging reminders of the oil rush of an earlier era. Today, the towns are thriving as 300-foot-tall wind turbines tower above those pumpjacks. Wind energy has become Texas’s latest boom, with the Lone Star State now leading the nation. How did this dramatic transformation happen in a place that fights federal environmental policies at every turn? In The Great Texas Wind Rush, environmental reporters Kate Galbraith and Asher Price tell the compelling story of a group of unlikely dreamers and innovators, politicos and profiteers. The tale spans a generation and more, and it begins with the early wind pioneers, precocious idealists who saw opportunity after the 1970s oil crisis. Operating in an economy accustomed to exploiting natural resources and always looking for the next big thing, their ideas eventually led to surprising partnerships between entrepreneurs and environmentalists, as everyone from Enron executives to T. Boone Pickens, as well as Ann Richards, George W. Bush and Rick Perry, ended up backing the new technology. In this down-to-earth account, the authors explain the policies and science that propelled the “windcatters” to reap the great harvest of Texas wind. They also explore what the future holds for this relentless resource that is changing the face of Texas energy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRenewable energy sourcesxTexas. 0aRenewable energy sourceszTexas. 0aWind powerxGovernment policyxTexas. 0aWind powerxGovernment policyzTexas. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh1 aPrice, Asher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73583540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292748798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292748798/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK